The Battle of the Lipari Islands, fought in 260 BC between Carthage and the Roman Republic, was a naval encounter in which 20 Carthaginian ships were defeated by 17 Roman ships. It was the first major naval confrontation of the Punic Wars and marked the start of a rivalry between the two sides. This led to a number of battles and naval encounters, including the Battle of the Salaminas and the Battle of the Marne, which were ultimately won by the Romans.
