Cueva de las Manos is a cave and complex of rock art sites located in the province of Santa Cruz, Argentina, which dates back to the Archaic period. It contains thousands of hand-stencilled rock art paintings. The site has been recognized as one of the best examples of early South American hunter-gatherer cultures. The site is currently considered an Important Cultural Property under UNESCO's World Heritage Status.
