The article provides information about Nestor Lakoba, an Abkhazian Communist leader who played a significant role in the establishment of Bolshevik power in Abkhazia. He served as the head of Abkhazia from 1922 until 1936, when he was forced to accept a lower status in the Soviet Union. Lakoba gained popularity among the Abkhaz population due to his ability to connect with them on a personal level. His relationship with Joseph Stalin led him to oppose collectivization in Abkhazia, resulting in his poisoning. After Stalin's death in 1953, Lakoba was rehabilitated and is now seen as a national hero in Abkhazia.
